\section{Study IV: Non-Causal Modeling and Reasoning Dynamics}
\label{sec:study4}

While the previous studies established the efficiency and scalability of \textsc{SDAR}, a fundamental question remains: does the shift from strictly causal autoregression to blockwise bidirectional diffusion alter the model's reasoning trajectory?
In this section, we investigate the impact of the \textsc{SDAR} paradigm on complex scientific reasoning. By adapting a science-specialized AR backbone (Qwen3-30B-A3B-Sci) into \textsc{SDAR}, we isolate the effects of the decoding paradigm on domain-specific knowledge application and test-time scaling.

\subsection{Domain Specialization via Local Bidirectionality}
\label{ssec:science_domain}

A theoretical advantage of blockwise diffusion is its ability to utilize local bidirectional attention within a generation block. This contrasts with AR, which is bound by a strict left-to-right causal mask.
Table~\ref{tab:ar_vs_sdar_science} presents the performance on specialized scientific benchmarks.

\paragraph{Non-causal modeling benefits structured domains.}
We observe a striking performance divergence based on the nature of the data. On tasks requiring linear logic (e.g., standard physics problems), \textsc{SDAR} maintains parity with the AR baseline.
However, on benchmarks involving highly structured data representations—specifically \textbf{ChemBench} (+12.3\%) and \textbf{GPQA-diamond} (+5.5\%)—\textsc{SDAR} significantly outperforms the AR baseline.
We attribute this to the model's ability to model non-sequential dependencies (e.g., molecular structures in SMILES format or complex chemical equations) more effectively within a diffusion block. The local bidirectional attention allows the model to refine structured tokens simultaneously rather than sequentially, overcoming the "causal bottleneck" inherent to AR processing of non-linguistic structures.

